Conceptual

Q1

$a)$ Overall performance of flexible methods will be better.

From equation 2.7, performance depends on minimizing $Variance$ (dependent on data set) and $Bias$ (dependent on flexibility)

  • Large sample size $n$ on $Variance$:
    • Inflexible models naturally has lower variance due to assumptions on the model
    • Flexible models have higher variance due to the degree of freedom it has; however, since $n$ is large, the effect is negligible \
    $\rarr$ Both types have roughly equal $Variance$
  • Small number of predictor $p$ on $Bias$:
    • Inflexible models tends to have higher bias due to assumptions on the model
    • Flexible models have lower bias (unless the true model is strictly linear in the first place). Additionally, small number of predictor $p$ also helps to reduce the complexity of the model, meaning that it's less likely to overfit the model
    $\rarr$ Flexible models have lower $Bias$ \

$b)$ Opposite effect of part ($a$) $\rarr$ Inflexible methods will perform better

$c)$ Assume small sample size, $Variance$ is large for both types. True model is highly non-linear $\rarr$ inflexible methods have higher $Bias$ $\rarr$ flexible methods perform better

$d)$ Var($\epsilon$) is the optimal model. As it is extremely high, regardless of model type, performance will not be good. But flexible methods also suffer from overfitting to the noise of the data, leading to higher $Variance$, this is avoided by inflexible methods. $Bias$ of inflexible methods are higher. However, since the true model is weak, it is likely that there is not real relationship between predictors and response, so the effect of $Bias$ is less.
Inflexible methods perform better

In[]:
from matplotlib.pyplot import subplots
import numpy as np
fig, ax = subplots(figsize=(4, 8))
x = np.linspace(0, 1, 100)
# Bias
y_bias = 0.01**x
# Variance
y_var = 0.01**(1-x)
# Irreducible error
y_irreducible = np.ones_like(x) + 0.1   # add 0.1 for visual separation between lines 
# Total loss
y_total = y_bias + y_var + y_irreducible

ax.set_xlabel('Flexibility')
ax.set_ylabel('Error')
ax.set_title('Bias-Variance Tradeoff')
y_types = [y_bias, y_var, y_irreducible, y_total]
for y_type in y_types:
    ax.plot(x, y_type)

Q4

Q5

  • Advantages:
    • Lower bias
    • More adaptable to complex model with non-linear relationship
  • Disadvanges:
    • Larger variance
    • Requires large amount of sample size, making it prone to overfitting
  • Preferable cases:
    • Problem with complex relationship
    • Prediction is more important than inference
  • Less preferable cases:
    • Problem with simple relationship
    • Inference is more important than prediction

Q6

  • $Parametric$ approaches:
    • Assume relationship between predictors and response (e.g. linear regression assumes linear relationship)
    • Train model by finding the coefficient for the assumed relationship (usually small)
  • $Non-parametric$ approaches:
    • No assumption on the relationship
    • Train model by finding large number of parameters
  • Advantages for parametric approaches:
    • Simpler model with high interpretability
    • Less dependent on data (low variance) $\rarr$ less prone to overfitting
  • Disadvantages:
    • Inflexible problems with complex relationships
    • Make assumptions on the model $\rarr$ high bias

test_point = np.array([0, 0, 0])

def find_euclidean_dist( df, x ):
    return np.sqrt(np.sum((df[['X1', 'X2', 'X3']] - x)**2, axis=1))

df['Euclid_dist'] = find_euclidean_dist( df, test_point )
df

def k_nearest(k):
    """Find most common `Y` from `df` from `k` nearest neighbors by Euclidean distance"""
    return df.nsmallest(k, columns='Euclid_dist')['Y'].mode()

def get_num_sub_from_predictor(predictor, amount):
    idx = Boston[predictor] > amount
    return Boston.loc[idx].shape[0]

print('Number of suburbs average more than 7 rooms per dwelling: ' + str(get_num_sub_from_predictor('rm', 7)))
print('Number of suburbs average more than 8 rooms per dwelling: ' + str(get_num_sub_from_predictor('rm', 8)))
